id to Moscow for its war in Ukraine.</p><p> Write to Michael R. Gordon at <a href="mailto:michael.gordon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">michael.gordon@wsj.com</a> and Nancy A. Youssef at <a href="mailto:nancy.youssef@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">nancy.youssef@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 02:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-and-china-sent-large-naval-patrol-near-alaska-127de28b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-and-china-sent-large-naval-patrol-near-alaska-127de28b<author><![CDATA[Michael R. GordonNancy A. Youssef]]></author><category> kwexclusive</category><category> Military Watercraft</category><category>航空航天/国防</category><category>国防设备/产品</category><category>工业品</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>International Relations</category><category> Navy</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>navy</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>military watercraft</category><category>航天</category><category>防御</category><category>国防装备</category><category>产品</category><category>工业品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[If All You Want Is Money, These Financial Advisers Might Say ‘No Thanks’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Advisers get pickier about clients or leave jobs they feel conflicted about <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001108588"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829437?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Elliot Dole, a financial adviser in St. Louis, has recently started to turn away prospective clients if they aren&#39;t interested in charitable giving.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Izaiah Johnson for The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001108588"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/joe-pinsker" itemprop="url" rel="author">Joe Pinsker</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 5, 2023 9:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/financial-advisors-money-job-satisfaction-happiness-20c40e17"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> People <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-to-tell-if-financial-adviser-doing-good-job-11672859927?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">seek out financial advisers</a> to help them preserve and grow their wealth. Some advisers don&#39;t want that to be their only job.</p><p> Elliot Dole&#39;s clients have net worths ranging from $3 million to $100 million. Dole, an adviser at Buckingham Strategic Wealth, an investment-advisory firm, has in the past few years started to turn away potential clients if they show no interest in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/getting-people-to-donate-more-to-charity-b2952379?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">donating some of their money</a> .</p><p> Many wealthy people, Dole said, default to giving everything they don&#39;t spend in their lifetime to family. “I don&#39;t think that&#39;s something that I want to be a part of if there&#39;s not some ante there—a commitment to give some money to charity,” he said. That philanthropic component has become an important part of his <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/workers-to-employers-were-just-not-that-into-you-71dbeb6e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">job satisfaction</a> , he said, and he personally donates money as well.</p><p> Advisers like Dole said making rich people richer as the sole goal of their work makes them uncomfortable. As a result, they might get pickier about who they take on or leave jobs they feel uneasy about—once they can afford to.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Dole, 45 years old, who lives in St. Louis and advises clients nationwide, said he worked for years before he felt secure enough, professionally and financially, to pick and choose his clients. “It&#39;s really hard to walk away from those shiny objects and those high-dollar engagements,” he said.</p><p> Advisers&#39; professional recalibrations are occurring alongside an increase in recent years, advisers say, in the number of conversations with clients that address personal values, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/how-to-use-investing-concepts-to-improve-your-life-6cd9e062?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">life goals</a> and well-being. As advisers discuss the bigger questions behind people&#39;s finances, some are asking themselves similar ones about their own work.</p><p> There are approximately 330,000 personal financial advisers in the US, according to the most recent data from the Bureau of Labor Statistics. The job&#39;s median pay was $95,390 in 2022, according to the BLS.</p><p> The country&#39;s financial advisers and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-officials-want-to-make-big-banks-bolster-their-financial-footing-5df6f40b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">wealth managers</a> collectively managed about $30.7 trillion in clients&#39; assets as of the end of 2021, according to estimates from Cerulli Associates, a financial-services consulting firm. That is up from $17.7 trillion at the end of 2016, in part because of rising asset values.</p><p> About 35% of advisers work primarily with clients who have $500,000 or less in assets available to invest, Cerulli Associates estimates. Some 19% work with those who have $2 million or more.</p><h3> Hoarding mentality</h3><p> Leighann Miko said she felt some “yuckiness” about work she did early in her career helping rich clients at wealth-advisory firms.</p><p> Miko, a financial planner in Portland, Ore., said her family was on welfare for much of her childhood, so the concept of having an abundance of money was foreign to her. At work, she was put off by what she viewed as some clients&#39; hoarding mentality—a desire to accumulate that ran counter to the communal support that got her through her youth. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="799" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829442?width=639&amp;height=799" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Leighann Miko likes working with clients who have large inheritances and want to give most of their money away.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mike Nelson</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “I&#39;m not looking to help Tom and Nancy buy their fourth home and new yacht,” she said.</p><p> Miko said she is generally fine with people spending their money as they please, but prefers to do different work. Many clients, for their part, might have little interest in what their adviser thinks of how they use their money.</p><p> Miko, who is 39, started her own firm, Equalis Financial, in 2016. Its primary clientele are LGBTQ people in creative industries and people with large inheritances who want to give away most of their money.</p><p> “Almost every single one of the clients that I have now who have inherited wealth and are looking to redistribute it have come from advisers who basically advised them against it,” she said.</p><p> Dole, at Buckingham Strategic Wealth, said that in his experience, people with a couple million dollars are more likely to donate than their counterparts with $20 million or more. He thinks this wealthier group often has an investing mind-set and hesitates to give away money when the return on their donation is hard to quantify.</p><h3> Professional misgivings</h3><p> Little is known about how those who advise the wealthiest clients feel about their work, said Brooke Harrington, a sociology professor at Dartmouth College who has researched the secretive global wealth-management industry for more than 15 years.</p><p> About one-quarter of the 65 wealth managers that Harrington interviewed for her research between 2007 and 2015 expressed qualms about the work they did reducing the tax liabilities of the ultrawealthy. One mentioned that he made a point of bringing up with his clients books about inequality by the economists Joseph Stiglitz and Amartya Sen.</p><p> Another quarter of the wealth managers Harrington interviewed voiced no unease and thought of themselves as defending their clients from unjustly high taxes. The remainder were aware of public criticism of their work, she said, but framed what they did in generally positive terms.</p><h3> &#39;Just to sound rich&#39;</h3><p> Sarah Behr started her own firm in 2017, after stints at large banks working with clients whose net worths ranged from $10 million to $300 million. Helping that group grow their wealth wasn&#39;t fulfilling, said Behr, the founder of Simplify Financial Planning in San Francisco. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="799" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829441?width=639&amp;height=799" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Sarah Behr wasn&#39;t fulfilled by her work with wealthy clients at large banks, so she started her own financial-planning firm.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Sean Behr</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “I didn&#39;t continue to be involved in a system that I didn&#39;t think was serving society that much,” said Behr, 44. “My protest was leaving.”</p><p> Now, Behr said she is able to provide financial advice to a wider range of clients because she made her firm&#39;s fees more affordable. She charges all clients the same one-time fees for sessions, rather than ongoing fees based on their portfolio size, as many advisers and wealth managers do. Some of her clients have millions of dollars in stock compensation from tech companies, but others are schoolteachers, artists and nurses.</p><p> When a prospective client is enthusiastic about investing in private equity, real estate or crypto, though, Behr takes it as a sign that they might not be a good match. She isn&#39;t opposed to those investments but finds that many people view them as quick paths to wealth.</p><p> “Sometimes, I think it&#39;s just to sound rich,” Behr said of those investments&#39; appeal. “I don&#39;t really know that I want to help you get to that.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> 分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What are your top priorities when it comes to financial planning?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Write to Joe Pinsker at <a href="mailto:joe.pinsker@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">joe.pinsker@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/financial-advisors-money-job-satisfaction-happiness-20c40e17</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/financial-advisors-money-job-satisfaction-happiness-20c40e17<author><![CDATA[Joe Pinsker]]></author><category>摄影委托</category><category>wsjlifework</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Charities/Volunteering</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>charities</category><category> volunteering</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[With China Attending, Ukraine Peace Discussions Inch Forward]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Saudi-hosted talks, which excluded Russia, narrowed gaps between Ukraine and major developing countries over fair conditions to end the war <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113797"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830480?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ukraine&#39;s President Volodymr Zelensky has pushed his ambassadors to intensify efforts to win global support for Kyiv&#39;s position.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: POU/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113797"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/laurence-norman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Laurence Norman</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stephen-kalin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Stephen Kalin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 5, 2023 6:09 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/with-china-attending-ukraine-peace-discussions-inch-forward-40855818"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Efforts to forge an international consensus around a durable and fair peace settlement to the war in Ukraine inched forward Saturday after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-saudi-arabias-ukraine-peace-talks-how-to-measure-success-fedb58ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">discussions in Saudi Arabia</a> among senior officials from 42 countries, including the US, China, India and Ukraine.</p><p> Ukraine and its Western backers have pitched the talks as an effort to rally global support behind conditions for ending the war that would favor Ukraine. Many big developing countries have been largely neutral on the conflict.</p><p> After the talks in Jeddah concluded, diplomats said there was broad acceptance that central principles of international law, like respect for Ukraine&#39;s sovereignty and territorial integrity, should be at the heart of future peace talks between Ukraine and Russia. There was agreement on pursuing more detailed work on the global impact of the war, and most countries attending, including China, appeared willing to meet again in the coming weeks in the current format, with Russia excluded, according to people involved in or briefed on the closed-door talks.</p><p> The Jeddah talks came after initial discussions in Copenhagen in June. US and European officials have stressed that the discussions aren&#39;t negotiations to end the conflict and won&#39;t seek to prescribe specific terms for a settlement.</p><p> The meeting&#39;s location Saturday carried important symbolism, as Ukraine, the US and Europe have pushed to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-to-host-ukraine-peace-talks-as-part-of-western-effort-to-woo-global-south-244f03f0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">bolster support for Kyiv in the global south</a> . Western diplomats have said the kingdom was picked to host partly in hopes of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-drawn-out-ukraine-war-opens-new-risks-for-china-e5fe8b7c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">persuading China to participate</a> , as Riyadh and Beijing maintain close ties.</p><p> Saudi Arabia is trying to play a larger role in diplomacy on Ukraine, after the US accused it last year of siding with Russia to keep oil prices high—thus bolstering Moscow&#39;s finances.</p><p> “A lot of credit to the Saudi hosts for the diplomatic engagement,” a US official said.</p><p> Many Western capitals are deeply skeptical that Russian President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">Vladimir Putin</a> is interested in pursuing peace talks this year. Russia has shown no signs of backing away from maximalist demands such as the recognition of its annexations of Ukrainian territory, including areas of Ukraine its military doesn&#39;t control.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Moscow has sent mixed signals about the talks. The Kremlin has suggested it would be watching closely, but Russia&#39;s Foreign Ministry spokeswoman called the discussions a hoax.</p><p> Ukraine&#39;s President Volodymr Zelensky pushed his ambassadors this week to intensify efforts to win global support for Kyiv&#39;s position. While diplomats talked in Jeddah, Russia launched fresh missile attacks on Ukraine.</p><p> “Russia unleashed another salvo of missiles on Ukraine this Saturday. Russia won&#39;t stop until it is stopped,” Ukraine&#39;s Foreign Minister Dmytro Kuleba tweeted. “The global community must focus on enforcing a just and lasting peace.”</p><p> The biggest difference between the Copenhagen and Jeddah meetings was attendance—more than twice as many countries attended or dialed into Saturday&#39;s talks. That included European countries, Japan, South Korea, Indonesia, Turkey and South Africa.</p><p> Most significantly China, which was invited to Copenhagen but stayed away, sent a delegation to Jeddah. Western diplomats said <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-allies-look-at-potential-china-role-in-ending-ukraine-war-2d6cbb4d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Beijing played a generally constructive role</a> in the talks.</p><p> As Russia&#39;s most important foreign ally, China is seen as crucial to building traction behind the talks and potentially offers a way to feed into the discussions some of Moscow&#39;s red lines and concerns, diplomats have said. Saudi Arabia&#39;s top leadership and Ukraine had pushed hard for Beijing to attend.</p><p> During the talks, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-urges-cessation-of-hostilities-peace-talks-to-end-ukraine-war-ae45829a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">China presented a 12-point plan</a> for a cease-fire and peace talks to end the war, which it first announced in February. European diplomats pushed back to warn that an unconditional cease-fire could simply create a frozen conflict and allow Russia to consolidate its control of Ukrainian territory.</p><p> “They got live feedback, which was a good exchange,” said a person familiar with the discussion.</p><p> A senior US official said that national security adviser Jake Sullivan and Undersecretary of State for Political Affairs Victoria Nuland met with the head of the Chinese delegation, Beijing&#39;s peace envoy Li Hui, on the sidelines.</p><p> “It was very good to have the Chinese here,” the US official said.</p><p> Diplomats also said some of the differences that emerged in Copenhagen appeared to have narrowed. In those talks, Ukraine pushed for major developing countries to accept Zelensky&#39;s peace plan, at the heart of which is a demand that peace begin only when Russian forces fully withdraw, and several developing countries said they wouldn&#39;t do so.</p><p> In Jeddah, Ukraine and the major developing countries appeared keener to seek out a consensus. A senior European official said that Ukraine didn&#39;t push again for its peace plan to be accepted and other countries weren&#39;t insisting that Kyiv drop it. Nor was there any crossfire over Ukraine&#39;s demand for the withdrawal of Russian troops. Ukraine didn&#39;t press the point, two diplomats said, nor was it challenged by developing countries.</p><p> While no date has been set for a third meeting, there was agreement on a two-track process to move forward. Ukraine will continue discussions with foreign ambassadors in Kyiv on peace conditions.</p><p> Saudi Arabia plans to propose a set of working groups for specific issues raised in the Ukrainian peace plan, some of which touch on the global impact of the war. That could include nuclear safety, environmental spillovers and food security—a concern underscored in recent days by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-says-it-is-pulling-out-of-ukraine-grain-deal-68190d1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the collapse</a> of the United Nations-brokered Black Sea grain initiative.</p><p> “The consensus is that this isn&#39;t a European war, but has impact on food, energy and economic stability globally and that it will take everyone on board to get to the final outcome of a settlement,” said a diplomat from one of the non-Western countries.</p><p> Write to Laurence Norman at <a href="mailto:laurence.norman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">laurence.norman@wsj.com</a> and Stephen Kalin at <a href="mailto:stephen.kalin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">stephen.kalin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 22:09:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/with-china-attending-ukraine-peace-discussions-inch-forward-40855818</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/with-china-attending-ukraine-peace-discussions-inch-forward-40855818<author><![CDATA[Laurence NormanStephen Kalin]]></author><category> ukraine</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>International Relations</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Pakistan Convicts Opposition Figure, Signals Election Delay]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>经过数段军事统治后，这两项举措危及脆弱的民主<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113250"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830443?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">前总理伊姆兰·汗于今年夏天早些时候离开法庭。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：aamir qureshi/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113250"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/saeed-shah" itemprop="url" rel="author">赛义德·沙阿</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 5 日下午 2:10（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-pakistani-prime-minister-imran-khan-convicted-in-corruption-case-749f405c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>巴基斯坦伊斯兰堡——周六，法院判处前总理伊姆兰·汗入狱，并且政府表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bombing-in-pakistan-kills-at-least-40-a86aa839?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">今年的选举</a>将被推迟，巴基斯坦停滞不前的民主进程遭遇挫折。</p><p>巴基斯坦有过四个直接军事统治时期。但自2008年以来，它经历了最长的民主政府时期。</p><p>据政府及其律师称，该国最大反对党领导人汗被伊斯兰堡一家法院判犯有腐败罪，并判处三年监禁。汗在本案以及自去年四月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supporters-of-pakistans-imran-khan-defy-top-court-block-vote-in-parliament-11649522558?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">被赶下台</a>以来政府针对他提起的数十起其他法律案件中坚称自己无罪。他的政党表示，他面临着一场将他从政坛驱逐出去的运动。如果定罪成立，汗先生将无法参加选举。</p><p>汗先生的一名律师表示，他计划对定罪提出上诉。周六判决后不久，警方在这位政客家中逮捕了他。</p><p>汗先生于 2018 年当选，去年因议会不信任投票而被罢免总理职务。还没有哪位巴基斯坦总理完成了完整的五年任期，每位总理都与该国军方发生过冲突。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830444?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴基斯坦拉合尔，警察在伊姆兰·汗的住所外守卫。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：KM Chaudary/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>另外，谢赫巴兹·谢里夫总理领导的政府周六表示，根据宪法规定原定于 11 月初举行的选举将被推迟。法律部长阿扎姆·纳齐姆·塔拉尔表示，宪法还要求根据最近的人口普查结果举行选举，这意味着需要更多时间准备，将投票时间推至2月左右。巴基斯坦今年早些时候进行了人口普查。他说，独立联邦机构巴基斯坦选举委员会将宣布新的选举日期。</p><p>该部长表示，投票可能会在明年二月或三月举行。但巴基斯坦许多人担心，如果选举不能按宪法规定举行，推迟的时间可能会更长。</p><p> “民主的未来是黯淡的，”巴基斯坦律师协会前副主席、律师阿比德·萨奇说。 “当整个宪法都陷入沉睡时，我认为在不久的将来不会举行选举。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830465?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">前总理伊姆兰·汗周六被捕后被护送穿过伊斯兰堡。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：WK Yousafzai/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>导致汗被定罪的案件与汗担任首相时沙特王储穆罕默德·本·萨勒曼送给他的一块手表有关。该手表后来被可汗卖掉了。他否认此次出售有任何不当行为。汗担任总理期间正式赠送给他的其他礼物也在该案中。</p><p>这款定制的镶钻手表的表盘上印有天房的图片，天房是沙特阿拉伯麦加的一座石头建筑，穆斯林前往那里朝圣。</p><p>根据法律，总理可以按照其价值的一部分购买此类官方礼物。政府声称，为汗购买手表进行的估价以及销售礼物收益的披露存在违规行为。法院在有罪裁决中表示，汗的“不诚实行为已毫无疑问”。</p><p> “政客们会因为这些鸡毛蒜皮的小事而名誉扫地，”立法者莫辛·达瓦尔（Mohsin Dawar）在 X（以前称为 Twitter）网站上表示，他所在的政党是现任联合政府的一小部分。 “政客不断地被利用，然后像伊姆兰·汗一样被抛弃。我们一直在原地打转。”</p><p>近几个月来， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistan-clinches-3-billion-in-imf-rescue-lending-698e63ce?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">陷入严重经济危机的</a>巴基斯坦遭遇了对汗及其领导的正义运动党的广泛政治镇压。今年早些时候，数千名汗的支持者因腐败指控而在军事场所举行抗议活动后被捕。几天后，法院将他保释出狱。</p><p> “我呼吁你们不要安静地坐在家里，”汗在他早些时候录制的视频中说，他预计自己会再次被捕。周六，法院宣布判决后，他的政党分享了这段视频。 “我的奋斗不是为了获取任何个人利益——我这样做是为了国家、为了你们、为了你们孩子的未来。如果你不捍卫自己的权利，你就会像奴隶一样生活。”</p><p>前板球明星汗被认为在 2018 年大选中得到了巴基斯坦强大军方的支持。被赶下台后，他发起了一场激烈的抗议活动，指责军方与其他政党合谋罢免他。军方和执政党否认这一说法，称他是通过民主方式被解职的。</p><p>对入狱的恐惧继续困扰着他的支持者，只有少数人出来抗议周六的判决。许多人在汗家外被警察围捕。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830466?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周六，伊姆兰·汗被定罪时，安全人员在伊斯兰堡站岗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：WK Yousafzai/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>汗的法律团队表示，此案没有遵循正当程序，包括给他们足够的时间传唤所有辩方证人。</p><p>政府否认逮捕与即将到来的选举有关，并表示法律正在按计划进行。</p><p> “伊姆兰必须为掌权期间的错误承担责任，”信息部长玛丽尤姆·奥朗则布 (Marriyum Aurangzeb) 表示。</p><p>本届议会最晚将于8月12日结束，需要一个本应保持中立的看守政府主持选举期间。</p><p>现在，看守政府的任期将超过宪法规定的90天期限。看守政府比政治政府更容易受到军方压力。巴基斯坦最近加强了看守政府的决策权，允许其与外国政府达成协议。</p><p>政府和军方仍然对汗的支持感到紧张，一些立法者和政治专家表示，他们认为这就是推迟选举决定的原因。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——瓦卡尔·吉拉尼 (Waqar Gillani) 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Saeed Shah，邮箱为<a href="mailto:saeed.shah@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">saeed.shah@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 18:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-pakistani-prime-minister-imran-khan-convicted-in-corruption-case-749f405c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-pakistani-prime-minister-imran-khan-convicted-in-corruption-case-749f405c<author><![CDATA[Saeed Shah]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Elections</category><category> National/Presidential Elections</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>presidential elections </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. Warns of Trade Fight Over Canada’s Digital Tax]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>尽管其他国家同意将全球科技税收协议推迟到 2025 年，但加拿大仍在继续征税<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107767"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="588" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829205?width=860&amp;height=588" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">加拿大总理贾斯汀·特鲁多和财政部长克里斯蒂亚·弗里兰表示，加拿大不能支持延长暂停征收数字税。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：帕特里克·多伊尔/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107767"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paul-vieira" itemprop="url" rel="author">Paul Vieira</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 5 日上午 11:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-warns-of-trade-fight-over-canadas-digital-tax-plan-751ffa30"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>渥太华——加拿大计划于 2024 年初征收数字服务税，此举违背了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-minimum-tax-deal-advances-with-partial-reprieve-for-u-s-based-companies-11675363954?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">全球关于重组国际税收的共识</a>，并招致了美国官员的批评。</p><p>拜登政府的高级成员正试图说服加拿大放弃其数字税收计划。美国和加拿大商界领导人表示，渥太华此举将损害商业，并使<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/usmca-takes-effect-but-north-american-trade-tensions-remain-11593604807?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">北美贸易协议</a>的未来受到质疑。</p><p>加拿大财政部长 Chrystia Freeland 上个月表示，加拿大将从 2024 年 1 月 1 日开始对科技公司向加拿大用户提供数字服务或销售加拿大用户数据的收入征收 3% 的税，并将追溯至 2022 年的收入。该税对加拿大的国家利益很重要。</p><p>信息技术领域的公司目前可以在全球范围内开展业务，同时将利润集中在本国或小型低税收司法管辖区；然后，他们在许多用户所在的国家缴纳相对较少的税。</p><p> 2021 年秋季达成的全球税收协定代表着<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/negotiators-see-global-deal-on-taxing-big-tech-companies-within-reach-36b47b10?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">跨国公司在全球的征税</a>方式、地点和数额的变化，但尚未实施。该协议旨在重新分配全球约 2000 亿美元企业利润的税收，此举旨在使税收制度适应信息技术进步带来的国际经营新方式。</p><p>加拿大在签署全球协议时提出了一项警告：如果在 2024 年初之前未实施，加拿大将征收自己的数字服务税。加拿大于 2020 年秋季首次提出对科技公司征税的计划，预计自 2022 年 1 月起开始征收。</p><p>上个月在巴黎，138 个国家同意将税收协议第一阶段<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-companies-score-partial-reprieve-from-global-minimum-tax-deal-c5c14d87?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的实施推迟一年</a>，即 2025 年初。加拿大不同意推迟，并表示将继续实施自己的数字服务计划税。周五，加拿大发布了关于如何应用拟议数字税的指南。</p><p>弗里兰表示，渥太华早些时候决定将数字税推迟两年，尽管其他欧洲国家保留了先前存在的数字税，“这是加拿大的重大让步”，并且加拿大不能支持延长暂停征收数字税。</p><p>与数字税相关的措施与另一项全球协议是分开的，该协议也是由经济合作与发展组织牵头的，该协议对每个经营所在国家的大公司征收<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-tax-mess-awaits-u-s-companies-and-congress-isnt-helping-eec13f2c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">15% 的最低税</a>，尽管这些协议具有政治联系。</p><p>美国贸易代表凯瑟琳·戴敦促渥太华<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-urges-canada-to-abandon-digital-service-tax-11645554146?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">放弃征税</a>，美国驻加拿大大使戴维·科恩上个月在加拿大《国家邮报》发表的采访中表示，“如果加拿大决定单独行动，美国将一无所有”。为了应对这种情况，我们只能选择在贸易背景下（可能是在数字贸易背景下）采取报复措施。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829210?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美国贸易代表凯瑟琳·戴呼吁加拿大放弃数字服务税。</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: BLAIR GABLE/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国驻渥太华大使馆发言人没有回应进一步置评的请求。</p><p>方慧兰表示，加拿大官员仍在与七国集团官员就妥协方案进行谈判，使加拿大的利益“能够得到保护和承认”。</p><p>在经合组织主导的谈判达成全球税收协议之前，包括法国、英国和意大利在内的许多欧洲国家已经引入了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-european-nations-claim-progress-on-path-to-removing-digital-taxes-11634244167?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">数字服务税</a>。该协议包括在协议生效之前暂停征收新的数字服务税。现有的数字税（例如欧洲的数字税）仍在适用，但一旦协议生效，这些税将被撤销。加拿大官员表示，一些欧洲司法管辖区向<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">元平台</a>和谷歌母公司征税是不公平的</p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="company-name">Alphabe</a> t 但加拿大不能。<p></p><p>美国贸易代表认为，加拿大提议的数字服务税具有歧视性，并且对美国商业造成负担，因为该行业由美国公司主导。法国的税收促使特朗普政府准备在2020年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-suspends-plan-to-impose-tariffs-on-french-luxury-goods-11610041797?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对法国奢侈品征收25%的关税</a>。在达成暂定的全球税收协议后，这一威胁被撤销。</p><p>全球税收协议最终可能不会达成。在美国，国会议员对此存在分歧，众议院共和党资深人士警告拜登政府，经合组织协议可能会扩大其他国家的征税权限，从而违反美国的税收协定。</p><p>美国财政部高级税务官员迈克尔·普洛吉安 (Michael Plowgian) 告诉国会，包括财政部长珍妮特·耶伦 (Janet Yellen) 在内的政府官员，</p>正在与加拿大同行交谈，“劝阻他们实施歧视性的”数字服务税。<p></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> 分享你的意见</h4><p><em>如果加拿大征收数字服务税，美国应如何应对？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>普洛吉安上个月在众议院筹款委员会作证时表示，最近在巴黎举行的经合组织税收谈判中，“加拿大在这个问题上处于孤立状态”。 “对于加拿大，我们正在探索所有选择，我们希望与国会合作解决这个问题。”</p><p>谷歌和Meta的代表提到了各自高管此前的言论，他们在言论中表示支持就科技公司税收待遇达成多边协议。加拿大和这两家科技公司目前正在就渥太华计划迫使它们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-passes-law-forcing-facebook-google-to-pay-media-for-links-f3e13300?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">向在其平台上发布链接的新闻机构进行赔偿的</a>计划发生争议。 Meta 本周表示，为了回应加拿大的措施，它已开始<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-platforms-to-begin-blocking-news-for-canadian-users-35d35b2b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阻止加拿大用户访问 Facebook 和 Instagram 上的新闻链接</a>。</p><p>推动华盛顿对加拿大施加经济压力的是加拿大最大的商业游说团体美国商会。</p><p> “加拿大曾表示希望维护经合组织的进程，但其最近的行动有点掩盖了这一点，”该商会美洲区高级副会长尼尔·赫林顿(Neil Herrington)表示。赫林顿补充说，加拿大的数字税可能会促使其他国家在达成全球协议之前征收类似的税，从而破坏经合组织的谈判。</p><p>加拿大商业委员会主席戈尔迪·海德 (Goldy Hyder) 表示，弗里兰需要重新考虑，并警告称，当美国-墨西哥-加拿大贸易条约于 2026 年接受立法审查时，数字服务税可能会使说服国会续签该条约的努力变得更加复杂。</p><p> “这与税收无关，而是与贸易有关，”代表加拿大最大公司首席执行官的海德说。</p><p>写信给保罗·维埃拉（Paul Vieira）： <a href="mailto:paul.vieira@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">paul.vieira@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 15:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-warns-of-trade-fight-over-canadas-digital-tax-plan-751ffa30</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-warns-of-trade-fight-over-canadas-digital-tax-plan-751ffa30<author><![CDATA[Paul Vieira]]></author><category>贸易/外部支付</category><category>实物贸易</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>字母 C1A</category><category>谷歌</category><category>贸易</category><category>外部支付</category><category>实物贸易</category><category>经济新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Police Pursuit of U.S.-Based Activist Embroils Family in Hong Kong]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着当局加大对流亡异见人士的压力，袁国强的亲属，包括一名亲北京议员，在中国城市被拘留和审问<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113271"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827461?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">香港立法会议员容尤妮是美国活动人士袁艾文的儿媳。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：TYRONE SIU/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113271"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：于<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/elaine-yu" itemprop="url" rel="author">伊莱恩</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 5 日上午 6:50 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/police-pursuit-of-u-s-based-activist-embroils-family-in-hong-kong-31ae1248"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>香港——黎明时分，香港国安警察闯入袁国强和容尤妮丝的公寓。袁国强和容尤妮丝是一位知名民主运动人士的儿子和儿媳，他们在国外批评中国共产党。 。</p><p>警方在上周一的突袭中查获了一台笔记本电脑和手机，并将袁和容（香港立法机构中的亲北京政客）带到警察局，对他们持不同政见亲属的活动进行了数小时的询问，然后在未经许可的情况下将他们释放。容说，指控。</p><p> 74 岁的美国活动家袁埃尔默 (Elmer Yuen) 是当局愤怒的焦点，他是八名海外批评中国的人之一，他们因被指控犯有国家安全罪而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hong-kong-takes-its-crackdown-abroad-e626bb6c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在香港面临逮捕令</a>。他上个月出席了华盛顿举行的新闻发布会，周二又出席了伦敦举行的新闻发布会，讨论了组建非官方流亡政府的计划。</p><p> Elmer Yuen 在网上发布的长视频中分享了他的政治评论，他表示，当局对其家人采取的行动是为了迫使他少说话并停止他的政治努力。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827463?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">民主活动人士袁埃尔默在旧金山中国领事馆外举行抗议活动。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Michael Ho Wai Lee/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “我当然担心我和家人的安全，但我们的工作有目标，必须付出代价，”他告诉《华尔街日报》。他说，“即使他们逮捕了我的全家”，他也不会被吓倒。</p><p>近年来，这个家族及其成员的广泛政治分歧一直是香港公众讨论的话题。他们出现在香港公共广播电台香港电台 2020 年播出的一部纪录片中，他们的故事引起了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mom-says-come-home-hong-kong-protests-divide-families-11567458226?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">政治分裂家庭中许多香港人</a>的共鸣。</p><p>容是一个主要亲北京政党的副主席。她的丈夫曾经开玩笑说，他们女儿家里的蜡笔少了一支黄色的——这座城市民主运动的颜色——因为他的妻子把它拿走了。</p><p>容接受询问后表示，她正在全力配合调查人员，并希望她的岳父和其他持不同政见者尽快被捕。 “如果我知道他的下落，我毫无疑问会透露，”她说。</p><p>容和她的丈夫没有回应置评请求。</p><p>香港行政长官李家超鼓励<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hong-kong-arrests-four-accused-of-aiding-overseas-activists-6636c125?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">被通缉的持不同政见者的朋友和亲戚</a>分享线索，并表示，如果抓获每名持不同政见者，他们和其他公众有资格获得约 128,000 美元的悬赏。</p><p>他说，当局将“走到天涯海角”追捕他们。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827471?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">香港行政长官李家超鼓励持不同政见者的亲属分享有关他们的信息。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：艾萨克·劳伦斯/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>许多海外异见人士通常居住在近年来因政治问题而暂停与香港引渡协议的国家，他们公开与香港的家人保持距离。</p><p>当被问及袁的家人时，警方表示，他们上周一带走了一名男子和两名女子，周四又带走了另外三人，但没有透露他们的姓名。警方表示，将采取一切必要措施逮捕那些被指控危害国家安全的人，并切断他们的经济支持。</p><p>国家安全警察高级官员李锐表示，逮捕令和悬赏金旨在帮助警方准备和收集证据，以便在持不同政见者返回香港时对其进行起诉。</p><p>北京于 2020 年实施的国家安全法<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hong-kong-police-arrest-six-for-sedition-in-fresh-crackdown-11674046056?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">被用来镇压异见</a>，数十名反对共产党统治的人被关押，民主媒体和团体被迫关闭，公众抗议活动被有效禁止。</p><p>超过 10 万人离开这座城市前往英国，数十名活动人士和政客已逃往那里和其他安全避难所。</p><p>美国和英国政府批评香港当局利用国安法追捕海外异见人士。北京指责外国“窝藏罪犯”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827475?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">袁国强 (Elmer Yuen) 之子袁国强 (Derek Yuen) 认为自己不属于政治分歧的任何一方。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：TYRONE SIU/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>连年的政治动荡，给许多香港家庭带来了摩擦。袁氏家族是香港政治谱系的缩影，也是香港电台节目中的特色之一，但在国家安全法实施后，袁氏家族的分歧已成为一道鸿沟。</p><p>在2019年大规模民主抗议活动和随后的镇压之前的几年里，随着支持或反对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hong-kongs-crackdown-on-dissent-hits-facebook-pages-11660645491?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">北京加强对香港控制的</a>观点日趋强硬，家人会在特殊场合聚会。</p><p>容2018年与德里克结婚后，容表示她基本上避免讨论政治。 “我会坐在一旁，照顾孩子，端上一些茶，”她在纪录片中说道。 “有一种默契，如果你不说，我不会说，但如果有人说了，我无疑会说出来。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您的家族史中是否有过有人因为发声而成为攻击目标的经历？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>这一集发生在国安法生效几个月后，以及袁艾玛离开香港之后<strong>。</strong></p><p>学者兼报纸专栏作家德里克·袁(Derek Yuen)认为自己站在政治分歧的任何一边，他当时表示，这是一场悲剧，他的父亲一开始就没有花太多时间陪伴孙子们，他可能永远不会回来到香港。</p><p>老袁在海外加倍积极活动，游说华盛顿的政客。去年，他和其他活动人士呼吁香港建立一种流亡议会，遭到香港政府的谴责。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827480?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">香港高等法院外的警察。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：路易丝·德尔莫特/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>此后不久，他的儿媳妇容就与他断绝关系，并在报纸上刊登广告，称自己是“一个流淌着伟大祖国血液的中国人”。</p><p>纪录片播出三年后，风险更大了。任何因协助通缉活动人士而被指控并被判有罪的人都将面临长期监禁。</p><p> 7月初，容在当地一个受欢迎的广播节目中表示，她曾警告她的丈夫不要与他父亲有联系：“你需要小心，比如见到他和金钱问题，”她说她告诉过他。</p><p>写信给Elaine Yu： <a href="mailto:elaine.yu@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">elaine.yu@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 10:50:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/police-pursuit-of-us-based-activist-embroils-family-in-hong-kong-31ae1248</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/police-pursuit-of-us-based-activist-embroils-family-in-hong-kong-31ae1248<author><![CDATA[Elaine Yu]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category></item></channel></rss>